  <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
    <li><strong>Method:</strong> Implanted depth electrodes in epilepsy patients undergoing pre-surgical monitoring — direct local field potential recording from hippocampal tissue</li>
    <li><strong>Intervention:</strong> 20 minutes of light-to-moderate stationary cycling</li>
    <li><strong>Primary finding:</strong> Increased frequency and amplitude of hippocampal sharp wave-ripples during and after exercise</li>
    <li><strong>Secondary finding:</strong> Strengthened functional connectivity between hippocampus and prefrontal and parietal memory networks within the same session</li>
    <li><strong>Proposed mechanism:</strong> Exercise-induced norepinephrine and dopamine release modulating hippocampal interneuron activity, plus increased cerebral blood flow enhancing inter-network coupling</li>
    <li><strong>Published:</strong> <em>Nature Neuroscience</em>, March 2026</li>
    <li><strong>Critical limitation:</strong> Epilepsy patient population with atypical neural architecture; generalizability to healthy brains unconfirmed</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<section id="the-timescale-problem" class="reveal">
  <h2>A Different Story About Time</h2>
  <p>The conventional account of exercise and brain health is a story about months. Run consistently for six months and your hippocampus may measurably increase in volume. Maintain an aerobic exercise habit and your BDNF levels — brain-derived neurotrophic factor, a protein that supports neuronal survival and synaptic plasticity — trend upward over time. The landmark 2011 study by Erickson and colleagues in <em>PNAS</em>, which found that a year of aerobic exercise increased hippocampal volume by approximately 2% in older adults (n=120), is the canonical reference point for this narrative. It is a compelling finding. It is also a finding about cumulative, long-term adaptation.</p>
  <p>The acute effects of exercise on cognition have been studied separately, and the literature there is reasonably consistent: a single bout of moderate aerobic exercise produces short-term improvements on tasks measuring executive function, attention, and episodic memory. A 2018 meta-analysis by Chang and colleagues in <em>Neuroscience and Biobehavioral Reviews</em> synthesized 79 studies and found reliable acute effects on cognitive performance, with effect sizes in the small-to-moderate range. But these studies measure behavioral output — performance on a test — not the neural mechanism producing it. They tell you something happened. They don't tell you what.</p>
  <p>The 2026 study tells you what. And the what is happening on a timescale that the behavioral literature could not resolve: within the exercise session itself, not hours later, not after weeks of training. The sharp wave-ripple system — the brain's memory consolidation machinery — is activating during the ride. This is not a refinement of the existing story about long-term neuroplasticity. It is a description of an acute neural event that the existing story had no framework to capture, because the existing story was built on methods that couldn't see it.</p>
  <p>Whether the acute ripple increase and the long-term volume change are related — whether one feeds the other, whether repeated acute activations accumulate into structural adaptation — is an open question. A plausible hypothesis, not yet a demonstrated mechanism.</p>
</section>

